data_combined <- min_wages %>% 
  left_join(us_states, by="region") 
plot1 <- data_combined %>% ggplot(aes(x=long,y=lat)) +
  geom_polygon(aes(group=group,
                   fill= (MinimumWageStandardWage))) +
  coord_map(projection = "albers",lat0=39,lat1=45) +
  theme_void() + theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  scale_fill_gradient(low="lightgreen",
                      high="darkgreen") +
  labs(title = "Minimum wage in US Sates in 2023",
       color="wage difference")

plot1

print("The map reveals a distinct pattern, highlighting the highest minimum wage rates in the western part of the United States. States in the central region generally maintain a minimum wage of around $10, while the southern regions exhibit the lowest rates, around $7.5. Notably, minimum wages experience an increase once again in the northeastern and southeastern part of the country. The data was extracted from 'https://worldpopulationreview.com/state-rankings/minimum-wage-by-state'")

varlist <- load_variables(2020, "acs5", cache=TRUE)
totalwfh_male_ACS <- get_acs(geography = "county",
                             variables = "B08406_034",
                             year = 2020,
                             survey = "acs5",
                             geometry = TRUE,
                             resolution="20m") %>%
  shift_geometry() %>%
  mutate(total_male_wfh= round(estimate))
Getting data from the 2016-2020 5-year ACS
ggplot(data = totalwfh_male_ACS) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill=log(total_male_wfh))) +
  scale_fill_gradient(low="pink",
                      high="purple") +
  labs(title="2020 Total Males Working From Home (log scale)",
       fill="Total Male wfh (log scale)") +
  theme_void() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

print("In 2020, the presence of males working from home is evident across all states in the US. Notably, the highest rates of males working remotely are concentrated in the western regions.
The analysis of the variable B08406_034, which represents the estimated count of males working from home within the entire population across all states in the year 2020. The data source is the 2016-2020 5-year American Community Survey (ACS) in the USA.")
